{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QcPxUvJaQ1VXmAp6RGzxgp","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→title: \"Scoring rules in `scoringutils`\"\n     3→author: \"Nikos Bosse\"\n     4→date: \"`r Sys.Date()`\"\n     5→output: rmarkdown::html_vignette\n     6→vignette: >\n     7→  %\\VignetteIndexEntry{Scoring rules in `scoringutils`}\n     8→  %\\VignetteEngine{knitr::rmarkdown}\n     9→  %\\VignetteEncoding{UTF-8}\n    10→bibliography: \"scoring-rules/scoringutils-package.bib\"\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→```{r, include = FALSE}\n    14→knitr::opts_chunk$set(\n    15→  fig.width = 7,\n    16→  collapse = TRUE,\n    17→  comment = \"#>\",\n    18→  cache = FALSE\n    19→)\n    20→library(scoringutils)\n    21→library(data.table)\n    22→```\n    23→\n    24→# Introduction\n    25→\n    26→This vignette gives an overview of the default scoring rules made available through the `scoringutils` package. You can, of course, also use your own scoring rules, provided they follow the same format. If you want to obtain more detailed information about how the package works, have a look at the [revised version](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1URaMsXmHJ1twpLpMl1sl2HW4lPuUycoj/view?usp=drive_link) of our `scoringutils` paper.\n    27→\n    28→We can distinguish two types of forecasts: point forecasts and probabilistic forecasts. A point forecast is a single number representing a single outcome. A probabilistic forecast is a full predictive probability distribution over multiple possible outcomes. In contrast to point forecasts, probabilistic forecasts incorporate uncertainty about different possible outcomes.\n    29→\n    30→Scoring rules are functions that take a forecast and an observation as input and return a single numeric value. For point forecasts, they take the form $S(\\hat{y}, y)$, where $\\hat{y}$ is the forecast and $y$ is the observation. For probabilistic forecasts, they usually take the form $S(F, y)$, where $F$ is the cumulative density function (CDF) of the predictive distribution and $y$ is the observation. By convention, scoring rules are usually negatively oriented, meaning that smaller values are better (the best possible score is usually zero). In that sense, the score can be understood as a penalty.\n    31→\n    32→Many scoring rules for probabilistic forecasts are so-called (strictly) proper scoring rules. Essentially, this means that they cannot be \"cheated\": A forecaster evaluated by a strictly proper scoring rule is always incentivised to report her honest best belief about the future and cannot, in expectation, improve her score by reporting something else. A more formal definition is the following: Let $G$ be the true, unobserved data-generating distribution. A scoring rule is said to be proper, if under $G$ and for an ideal forecast $F = G$, there is no forecast $F' \\neq F$ that in expectation receives a better score than $F$. A scoring rule is considered strictly proper if, under $G$, no other forecast $F'$ in expectation receives a score that is better than or the same as that of $F$.\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→# Metrics for point forecasts\n    37→\n    38→See a list of the default metrics for point forecasts by calling `get_metrics(example_point)`.\n    39→\n    40→This is an overview of the input and output formats for point forecasts:\n    41→\n    42→```{r, echo=FALSE, out.width=\"100%\", fig.cap=\"Input and output formats: metrics for point.\"}\n    43→knitr::include_graphics(file.path(\"scoring-rules\", \"input-point.png\"))\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→\n    47→## A note of caution\n    48→\n    49→Scoring point forecasts can be tricky business. Depending on the choice of the scoring rule, a forecaster who is clearly worse than another, might consistently receive better scores (see @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011 for an illustrative example).\n    50→\n    51→Every scoring rule for a point forecast is implicitly minimised by a specific aspect of the predictive distribution. The mean squared error, for example, is only a meaningful scoring rule if the forecaster actually reported the mean of their predictive distribution as a point forecast. If the forecaster reported the median, then the mean absolute error would be the appropriate scoring rule. If the scoring rule and the predictive task do not align, misleading results ensue. Consider the following example:\n    52→\n    53→```{r}\n    54→set.seed(123)\n    55→n <- 1000\n    56→observed <- rnorm(n, 5, 4)^2\n    57→\n    58→predicted_mu <- mean(observed)\n    59→predicted_not_mu <- predicted_mu - rnorm(n, 10, 2)\n    60→\n    61→mean(Metrics::ae(observed, predicted_mu))\n    62→mean(Metrics::ae(observed, predicted_not_mu))\n    63→\n    64→mean(Metrics::se(observed, predicted_mu))\n    65→mean(Metrics::se(observed, predicted_not_mu))\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→\n    69→\n    70→## Absolute error\n    71→\n    72→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n    73→\n    74→**Forecast**: $\\hat{y}$, a real number, the median of the forecaster's predictive distribution.\n    75→\n    76→The absolute error is the absolute difference between the predicted and the observed values. See `?Metrics::ae`.\n    77→\n    78→$$\\text{ae} = |y - \\hat{y}|$$\n    79→\n    80→The absolute error is only an appropriate rule if $\\hat{y}$ corresponds to the median of the forecaster's predictive distribution. Otherwise, results will be misleading (see @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011).\n    81→\n    82→## Squared error\n    83→\n    84→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n    85→\n    86→**Forecast**: $\\hat{y}$, a real number, the mean of the forecaster's predictive distribution.\n    87→\n    88→The squared error is the squared difference between the predicted and the observed values. See `?Metrics::se`.\n    89→\n    90→$$\\text{se} = (y - \\hat{y})^2$$\n    91→The squared error is only an appropriate rule if $\\hat{y}$ corresponds to the mean of the forecaster's predictive distribution. Otherwise, results will be misleading (see @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011).\n    92→\n    93→## Absolute percentage error\n    94→\n    95→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n    96→\n    97→**Forecast**: $\\hat{y}$, a real number\n    98→\n    99→The absolute percentage error is the absolute percent difference between the predicted and the observed values. See `?Metrics::ape`.\n   100→\n   101→$$\\text{ape} = \\frac{|y - \\hat{y}|}{|y|}$$\n   102→\n   103→The absolute percentage error is only an appropriate rule if $\\hat{y}$ corresponds to the $\\beta$-median of the forecaster's predictive distribution with $\\beta = -1$. The $\\beta$-median, $\\text{med}^{(\\beta)}(F)$, is the median of a random variable whose density is proportional to $y^\\beta f(y)$. The specific $\\beta$-median that corresponds to the absolute percentage error is $\\text{med}^{(-1)}(F)$. Otherwise, results will be misleading (see @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011).\n   104→\n   105→---\n   106→\n   107→# Binary forecasts\n   108→\n   109→See a list of the default metrics for point forecasts by calling `?get_metrics(example_binary)`.\n   110→\n   111→This is an overview of the input and output formats for point forecasts:\n   112→\n   113→```{r, echo=FALSE, out.width=\"100%\", fig.cap=\"Input and output formats: metrics for binary forecasts.\"}\n   114→knitr::include_graphics(file.path(\"scoring-rules\", \"input-binary.png\"))\n   115→```\n   116→\n   117→\n   118→## Brier score\n   119→\n   120→**Observation**: $y$, either 0 or 1\n   121→\n   122→**Forecast**: $p$, a probability that the observed outcome will be 1.\n   123→\n   124→The Brier score is a strictly proper scoring rule. It is computed as the mean squared error between the probabilistic prediction and the observed outcome.\n   125→\n   126→\\begin{equation}\n   127→    \\text{BS}(p, y) = (p - y)^2 =\n   128→    \\begin{cases}\n   129→        p^2,       & \\text{if } y = 1\\\\\n   130→        (1 - p)^2,   & \\text{if } y = 0\n   131→    \\end{cases}\n   132→\\end{equation}\n   133→\n   134→The Brier score and the logarithmic score (see below) differ in how they penalise over- and underconfidence (see @macheteContrastingProbabilisticScoring2012). The Brier score penalises overconfidence and underconfidence in probability space the same. Consider the following example:\n   135→\n   136→```{r}\n   137→n <- 1e6\n   138→p_true <- 0.7\n   139→observed <- factor(rbinom(n = n, size = 1, prob = p_true), levels = c(0, 1))\n   140→\n   141→p_over <- p_true + 0.15\n   142→p_under <- p_true - 0.15\n   143→\n   144→abs(mean(brier_score(observed, p_true)) - mean(brier_score(observed, p_over)))\n   145→abs(mean(brier_score(observed, p_true)) - mean(brier_score(observed, p_under)))\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→See `?brier_score()` for more information.\n   149→\n   150→\n   151→## Logarithmic score\n   152→\n   153→**Observation**: $y$, either 0 or 1\n   154→\n   155→**Forecast**: $p$, a probability that the observed outcome will be 1.\n   156→\n   157→The logarithmic score (or log score) is a strictly proper scoring rule. It is computed as the negative logarithm of the probability assigned to the observed outcome.\n   158→\n   159→\\begin{equation}\n   160→    \\text{Log score}(p, y) = - \\log(1 - |y - p|) =\n   161→    \\begin{cases}\n   162→        -\\log (p),       & \\text{if } y = 1\\\\\n   163→        -\\log (1 - p),   & \\text{if } y = 0\n   164→    \\end{cases}\n   165→\\end{equation}\n   166→\n   167→The log score penalises overconfidence more strongly than underconfidence (in probability space). Consider the following example:\n   168→\n   169→```{r}\n   170→abs(mean(logs_binary(observed, p_true)) - mean(logs_binary(observed, p_over)))\n   171→abs(mean(logs_binary(observed, p_true)) - mean(logs_binary(observed, p_under)))\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→See `?logs_binary()` for more information.\n   175→\n   176→\n   177→---\n   178→\n   179→# Sample-based forecasts\n   180→\n   181→See a list of the default metrics for sample-based forecasts by calling `get_metrics(example_sample_continuous)`.\n   182→\n   183→This is an overview of the input and output formats for quantile forecasts:\n   184→\n   185→```{r, echo=FALSE, out.width=\"100%\", fig.cap=\"Input and output formats: metrics for sample-based forecasts.\"}\n   186→knitr::include_graphics(file.path(\"scoring-rules\", \"input-sample.png\"))\n   187→```\n   188→\n   189→\n   190→## CRPS\n   191→\n   192→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   193→\n   194→**Forecast**: A continuous ($F$) or discrete ($P$) forecast.\n   195→\n   196→The continuous ranked probability score (CRPS) is popular in fields such as meteorology and epidemiology. The CRPS is defined as\n   197→$$\\text{CRPS}(F, y) = \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\left( F(x) - 1(x \\geq y) \\right)^2 dx,$$\n   198→where $y$ is the observed value and $F$ the CDF of predictive distribution.\n   199→\n   200→For discrete forecasts, for example count data, the ranked probability score (RPS) can be used instead and is commonly defined as:\n   201→$$ \\text{RPS}(P, y) = \\sum_{x = 0}^\\infty (P(x) - 1(x \\geq y))^2, $$\n   202→where $P$ is the cumulative probability mass function (PMF) of the predictive distribution.\n   203→\n   204→\n   205→The CRPS can be understood as a generalisation of the absolute error to predictive distributions [@gneitingStrictlyProperScoring2007]. It can also be understood as the integral over the Brier score for the binary probability forecasts implied by the CDF for all possible observed values. The CRPS is also related to the Cramér-distance between two distributions and equals the special case where one of the distributions is concentrated in a single point (see e.g. @zielEnergyDistanceEnsemble2021). The CRPS is a global scoring rule, meaning that the entire predictive distribution is taken into account when determining the quality of the forecast.\n   206→\n   207→`scoringutils` re-exports the `crps_sample()` function from the `scoringRules` package, which assumes that the forecast is represented by a set of samples from the predictive distribution. See `?crps_sample()` for more information.\n   208→\n   209→\n   210→### Overprediction, underprediction and dispersion\n   211→\n   212→The CRPS can be interpreted as a sum of a dispersion, an overprediction and an underprediction component.\n   213→If $m$ is the median forecast then the dispersion component is\n   214→$$\\text{CRPS}(F, m),$$\n   215→the overprediction component is\n   216→$$\n   217→\\begin{cases}\n   218→m > y & CRPS(F, y) - CRPS(F, m)\\\\\n   219→m \\leq y & 0\\\\\n   220→\\end{cases}\n   221→$$\n   222→and the underprediction component is\n   223→$$\n   224→\\begin{cases}\n   225→m < y & CRPS(F, y) - CRPS(F, m)\\\\\n   226→m \\geq y & 0\\\\\n   227→\\end{cases}\n   228→$$\n   229→\n   230→These can be accessed via the `dispersion_sample()`, `overprediction_sample()` and `underprediction_sample()` functions, respectively.\n   231→\n   232→## Log score\n   233→\n   234→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   235→\n   236→**Forecast**: A continuous ($F$) or discrete ($P$) forecast.\n   237→\n   238→The logarithmic scoring rule is simply the negative logarithm of the density of the the predictive distribution evaluated at the observed value:\n   239→\n   240→$$ \\text{log score}(F, y) = -\\log f(y), $$\n   241→\n   242→where $f$ is the predictive probability density function (PDF) corresponding to the Forecast $F$ and $y$ is the observed value.\n   243→\n   244→For discrete forecasts, the log score can be computed as\n   245→\n   246→$$ \\text{log score}(F, y) = -\\log p_y, $$\n   247→where $p_y$ is the probability assigned to the observed outcome $y$ by the forecast $F$.\n   248→\n   249→The logarithmic scoring rule can produce large penalties when the observed value takes on values for which $f(y)$ (or $p_y$) is close to zero. It is therefore considered to be sensitive to outlier forecasts. This may be desirable in some applications, but it also means that scores can easily be dominated by a few extreme values. The logarithmic scoring rule is a local scoring rule, meaning that the score only depends on the probability that was assigned to the actual outcome. This is often regarded as a desirable property for example in the context of Bayesian inference \\citep{winklerScoringRulesEvaluation1996}. It implies for example, that the ranking between forecasters would be invariant under monotone transformations of the predictive distribution and the target.\n   250→\n   251→`scoringutils` re-exports the `logs_sample()` function from the `scoringRules` package, which assumes that the forecast is represented by a set of samples from the predictive distribution. One implications of this is that it is currently not advisable to use the log score for discrete forecasts. The reason for this is that `scoringRules::logs_sample()` estimates a predictive density from the samples, which can be problematic for discrete forecasts.\n   252→\n   253→See `?logs_sample()` for more information.\n   254→\n   255→\n   256→## Dawid-Sebastiani score\n   257→\n   258→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   259→\n   260→**Forecast**: $F$. The predictive distribution with mean $\\mu$ and standard deviation $\\sigma$.\n   261→\n   262→The Dawid-Sebastiani score is a proper scoring rule that only relies on the first moments of the predictive distribution and is therefore easy to compute. It is given as\n   263→\n   264→$$\\text{dss}(F, y) = \\left( \\frac{y - \\mu}{\\sigma} \\right)^2 + 2 \\cdot \\log \\sigma.$$\n   265→\n   266→`scoringutils` re-exports the implementation of the DSS from the `scoringRules` package. It assumes that the forecast is represented by a set of samples drawn from the predictive distribution. See `?dss_sample()` for more information.\n   267→\n   268→## Dispersion - Median Absolute Deviation (MAD)\n   269→\n   270→**Observation**: Not required.\n   271→\n   272→**Forecast**: $F$, the predictive distribution.\n   273→\n   274→Dispersion (also called sharpness) is the ability to produce narrow forecasts. It is a feature of the forecasts only and does not depend on the observations. Dispersion is therefore only of interest conditional on calibration: a very precise forecast is not useful if it is clearly wrong.\n   275→\n   276→One way to measure sharpness (as suggested by @funkAssessingPerformanceRealtime2019) is the normalised median absolute deviation about the median (MADN) ). It is computed as\n   277→  $$ S(F) = \\frac{1}{0.675} \\cdot \\text{median}(|F - \\text{median(F)}|). $$\n   278→If the forecast $F$ follows a normal distribution, then sharpness will equal the standard deviation of $F$.For more details, see `?mad_sample()`.\n   279→\n   280→## Bias\n   281→\n   282→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   283→\n   284→**Forecast**: A continuous ($F$) or discrete ($P$) forecast.\n   285→\n   286→\n   287→Bias is a measure of the tendency of a forecaster to over- or underpredict. For *continuous* forecasts, the `scoringutils` implementation calculates bias as\n   288→$$B(F, y) = 1 - 2 \\cdot F (y), $$\n   289→where $F(y)$ is the empirical cumulative distribution function of the forecast evaluated at the observed value $y$. To handle ties appropriately (which can occur when predictions equal observations for example due to rounding), the implementation uses mid-ranks: $F(y)$ is computed as the proportion of predictions strictly less than $y$ plus half the proportion of predictions equal to $y$.\n   290→\n   291→\n   292→For *discrete* forecasts, we calculate bias as\n   293→$$B(P, y) = 1 - (P(y) + P(y + 1)). $$\n   294→where $P(y)$ is the cumulative probability assigned to all outcomes smaller or equal to $y$, i.e. the cumulative probability mass function.\n   295→\n   296→Bias is bound between -1 and 1 and represents the tendency of forecasts to be biased rather than the absolute amount of over- and underprediction (which is e.g. the case for the weighted interval score (WIS, see below).\n   297→\n   298→## Absolute error of the median\n   299→\n   300→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   301→\n   302→**Forecast**: A forecast $F$\n   303→\n   304→$$\\text{ae}_{\\text{median}}(F, y) = |\\text{median} (F) - y|.$$\n   305→See section [A note of caution] or @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011 for a discussion on the correspondence between the absolute error and the median.\n   306→\n   307→## Squared error of the mean\n   308→\n   309→**Observation**: $y$, a real number (or a discrete number).\n   310→\n   311→**Forecast**: A forecast $F$\n   312→\n   313→$$\\text{se}_{\\text{medn}}(F, y) = (\\text{mean} (F) - y)^2.$$\n   314→See section [A note of caution] or @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011 for a discussion on the correspondence between the squared error and the mean.\n   315→\n   316→---\n   317→\n   318→# Quantile-based forecasts\n   319→\n   320→See a list of the default metrics for quantile-based forecasts by calling `get_metrics(example_quantile)`.\n   321→\n   322→This is an overview of the input and output formats for quantile forecasts:\n   323→\n   324→```{r, echo=FALSE, out.width=\"100%\", fig.cap=\"Input and output formats: metrics for quantile-based forecasts.\"}\n   325→knitr::include_graphics(file.path(\"scoring-rules\", \"input-quantile.png\"))\n   326→```\n   327→\n   328→## Weighted interval score (WIS)\n   329→\n   330→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n   331→\n   332→**Forecast**: $F$. The CDF of the predictive distribution is represented by a set of quantiles. These quantiles form the lower ($l$) and upper ($u$) bounds of central prediction intervals.\n   333→\n   334→The weighted interval score (WIS) is a strictly proper scoring rule and can be understood as an approximation of the CRPS for forecasts in a quantile format (which in turn represents a generalisation of the absolute error). Quantiles are assumed to be the lower and upper bounds of prediction intervals symmetric around the median. For a single interval, the interval score is\n   335→\n   336→$$IS_\\alpha(F,y) = \\underbrace{(u-l)}_\\text{dispersion} + \\underbrace{\\frac{2}{\\alpha} \\cdot (l-y) \\cdot \\mathbf{1}(y \\leq l)}_{\\text{overprediction}} + \\underbrace{\\frac{2}{\\alpha} \\cdot (y-u) \\cdot \\mathbf{1}(y \\geq u)}_{\\text{underprediction}}, $$\n   337→\n   338→where $\\mathbf{1}()$ is the indicator function, and $l$ and $u$ are the $\\frac{\\alpha}{2}$ and $1 - \\frac{\\alpha}{2}$ quantiles of the predictive distribution $F$. $l$ and $u$ together form the prediction interval. The interval score can be understood as the sum of three components: dispersion, overprediction and underprediction.\n   339→\n   340→For a set of $K$ prediction intervals and the median $m$, the score is given as a weighted sum of individual interval scores, i.e.\n   341→\n   342→$$WIS = \\frac{1}{K + 0.5} \\cdot \\left(w_0 \\cdot |y - m| + \\sum_{k = 1}^{K} w_k \\cdot IS_{\\alpha_{k}}(F, y)\\right),$$\n   343→where $m$ is the median forecast and $w_k$ is a weight assigned to every interval. When the weights are set to $w_k = \\frac{\\alpha_k}{2}$ and $w_0 = 0.5$, then the WIS converges to the CRPS for an increasing number of equally spaced quantiles.\n   344→\n   345→See `?wis()` for more information.\n   346→\n   347→### Overprediction, underprediction and dispersion\n   348→\n   349→These are the individual components of the WIS. See `?overprediction_quantile()`, `?underprediction_quantile()` and `?dispersion_quantile()` for more information.\n   350→\n   351→## Bias\n   352→\n   353→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n   354→\n   355→**Forecast**: $F$. The CDF of the predictive distribution is represented by a set of quantiles, $Q$.\n   356→\n   357→Bias can be measured as\n   358→\n   359→\\begin{equation}\n   360→    \\text{B}(F, y) =\n   361→    \\begin{cases}\n   362→        (1 - 2 \\cdot \\max \\{\\alpha | q_\\alpha \\in Q \\land q_\\alpha \\leq y\\}),       & \\text{if } y < q_{0.5} \\quad \\text{(overprediction)}\\\\\n   363→        (1 - 2 \\cdot \\min \\{\\alpha | q_\\alpha \\in Q_t \\land q_\\alpha \\geq y\\},   & \\text{if } y > q_{0.5} \\quad \\text{(underprediction)}\\\\\n   364→        0,   & \\text{if } y = q_{0.5}, \\\\\n   365→    \\end{cases}\n   366→\\end{equation}\n   367→\n   368→where $q_\\alpha$ is the $\\alpha$-quantile of the predictive distribution. For consistency, we define $Q$ (the set of quantiles that form the predictive distribution $F$) such that it always includes the element $q_0 = -\\infty$ and $q_1 = \\infty$. In clearer terms, bias is:\n   369→\n   370→- $1 - (2 \\times$ the maximum percentile rank for which the corresponding quantile is still below the observed value), *if the observed value is smaller than the median of the predictive distribution.*\n   371→- $1 - (2 \\times$ the minimum percentile rank for which the corresponding quantile is still larger than the observed value) *if the observed value is larger than the median of the predictive distribution.*.\n   372→- $0$ *if the observed value is exactly the median*.\n   373→\n   374→Bias can assume values between -1 (underprediction) and 1 (overprediction) and is 0 ideally (i.e. unbiased).\n   375→\n   376→For an increasing number of quantiles, the percentile rank will equal the proportion of predictive samples below the observed value, and the bias metric coincides with the one for continuous forecasts (see above).\n   377→\n   378→See `?bias_quantile()` for more information.\n   379→\n   380→## Interval coverage\n   381→\n   382→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n   383→\n   384→**Forecast**: $F$. The CDF of the predictive distribution is represented by a set of quantiles. These quantiles form central prediction intervals.\n   385→\n   386→Interval coverage for a given interval range is defined as the proportion of observations that fall within the corresponding central prediction intervals. Central prediction intervals are symmetric around the median and formed by two quantiles that denote the lower and upper bound. For example, the 50% central prediction interval is the interval between the 0.25 and 0.75 quantiles of the predictive distribution.\n   387→\n   388→### Interval coverage deviation\n   389→\n   390→The interval coverage deviation is the difference between the observed interval coverage and the nominal interval coverage. For example, if the observed interval coverage for the 50% central prediction interval is 0.6, then the interval coverage deviation is $0.6 - 0.5 = 0.1.$\n   391→\n   392→$$\\text{interval coverage deviation} = \\text{observed interval coverage} - \\text{nominal interval coverage}$$\n   393→\n   394→## Absolute error of the median\n   395→\n   396→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n   397→\n   398→**Forecast**: $F$. The CDF of the predictive distribution is represented by a set of quantiles.\n   399→\n   400→The absolute error of the median is the absolute difference between the median of the predictive distribution and the observed value.\n   401→\n   402→$$\\text{ae}_\\text{median} = |\\text{median}(F) - y|$$\n   403→See section [A note of caution] or @gneitingMakingEvaluatingPoint2011 for a discussion on the correspondence between the absolute error and the median.\n   404→\n   405→\n   406→## Quantile score\n   407→\n   408→**Observation**: $y$, a real number\n   409→\n   410→**Forecast**: $F$. The CDF of the predictive distribution is represented by a set of quantiles.\n   411→\n   412→The quantile score, also called pinball loss, for a single quantile level $\\tau$ is defined as\n   413→\n   414→\\begin{equation}\n   415→    \\text{QS}_\\tau(F, y) = 2 \\cdot \\{ \\mathbf{1}(y \\leq q_\\tau) - \\tau\\} \\cdot (q_\\tau - y) =\n   416→    \\begin{cases}\n   417→        2 \\cdot (1 - \\tau) * q_\\tau - y,       & \\text{if } y \\leq q_\\tau\\\\\n   418→        2 \\cdot \\tau * |q_\\tau - y|,           & \\text{if } y > q_\\tau,\n   419→    \\end{cases}\n   420→\\end{equation}\n   421→\n   422→with $q_\\tau$ being the $\\tau$-quantile of the predictive distribution $F$, and $\\mathbf{1}(\\cdot)$ the indicator function.\n   423→\n   424→The (unweighted) interval score (see above) for a $1 - \\alpha$ prediction interval can be computed from the quantile scores at levels $\\alpha/2$ and $1 - \\alpha/2$ as\n   425→\n   426→$$\\text{IS}_\\alpha(F, y) = \\frac{\\text{QS}_{\\alpha/2}(F, y) + \\text{QS}_{1 - \\alpha/2}(F, y)}{\\alpha}$$.\n   427→\n   428→The weighted interval score can be obtained as a simple average of the quantile scores:\n   429→\n   430→$$\\text{WIS}_\\alpha(F, y) = \\frac{\\text{QS}_{\\alpha/2}(F, y) + \\text{QS}_{1 - \\alpha/2}(F, y)}{2}$$.\n   431→\n   432→See `?quantile_score` and @bracherEvaluatingEpidemicForecasts2021 for more details.\n   433→\n   434→\n   435→---\n   436→\n   437→# Additional metrics\n   438→\n   439→\n   440→## Quantile coverage\n   441→\n   442→Quantile coverage for a given quantile level is defined as the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the corresponding predictive quantiles. For example, the 0.5 quantile coverage is the proportion of observed values that are smaller than the 0.5-quantiles of the predictive distribution.\n   443→\n   444→<!-- ## Probability integral transform (PIT) -->\n   445→\n   446→\n   447→\n   448→\n   449→<!-- # Calibration -->\n   450→\n   451→<!-- Calibration or reliability of forecasts is the ability of a model to -->\n   452→<!-- correctly identify its own uncertainty in making predictions. In a model -->\n   453→<!-- with perfect calibration, the observed data at each time point look as if -->\n   454→<!-- they came from the predictive probability distribution at that time. -->\n   455→\n   456→<!-- Equivalently, one can inspect the probability integral transform of the -->\n   457→<!-- predictive distribution at time t, -->\n   458→\n   459→<!-- $$u_t = F_t (x_t)$$ -->\n   460→\n   461→<!-- where $x_t$ is the observed data point at time $t \\text{ in } t_1, …, t_n$, -->\n   462→<!-- n being the number of forecasts, and $F_t$ is the (continuous) predictive -->\n   463→<!-- cumulative probability distribution at time t. If the true probability -->\n   464→<!-- distribution of outcomes at time t is $G_t$ then the forecasts $F_t$ are -->\n   465→<!-- said to be ideal if $F_t = G_t$ at all times $t$. In that case, the -->\n   466→<!-- probabilities ut are distributed uniformly. -->\n   467→\n   468→<!-- In the case of discrete outcomes such as incidence counts, -->\n   469→<!-- the PIT is no longer uniform even when forecasts are ideal. -->\n   470→<!-- In that case a randomised PIT can be used instead: -->\n   471→\n   472→<!-- $$u_t = P_t(k_t) + v \\cdot (P_t(k_t) - P_t(k_t - 1) )$$ -->\n   473→\n   474→<!-- where $k_t$ is the observed count, $P_t(x)$ is the predictive -->\n   475→<!-- cumulative probability of observing incidence $k$ at time $t$, -->\n   476→<!-- $P_t (-1) = 0$ by definition and $v$ is standard uniform and independent -->\n   477→<!-- of $k$. If $P_t$ is the true cumulative -->\n   478→<!-- probability distribution, then $u_t$ is standard uniform. -->\n   479→\n   480→<!-- The function checks whether integer or continuous forecasts were provided. -->\n   481→<!-- It then applies the (randomised) probability integral and tests -->\n   482→<!-- the values $u_t$ for uniformity using the -->\n   483→<!-- Anderson-Darling test. -->\n   484→\n   485→<!-- As a rule of thumb, there is no evidence to suggest a forecasting model is -->\n   486→<!-- miscalibrated if the p-value found was greater than a threshold of $p >= 0.1$, -->\n   487→<!-- some evidence that it was miscalibrated if $0.01 < p < 0.1$, and good -->\n   488→<!-- evidence that it was miscalibrated if $p <= 0.01$. -->\n   489→<!-- In this context it should be noted, though, that uniformity of the -->\n   490→<!-- PIT is a necessary but not sufficient condition of calibration. It should -->\n   491→<!-- also be noted that the test only works given sufficient samples, otherwise the  -->\n   492→<!-- Null hypothesis will often be rejected outright.  -->\n   493→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01R8W1DdLe1soYYE3wWJ5nww","session_id":"a6c236b1-3281-41ca-b12f-868322653287","uuid":"f78b9333-d6a0-4456-977c-ebb7060725cd"}
